<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-244-209 </DOCNO><DOCID>09 786 139</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Jan 14 1991 n303 p55(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>And then there'll be one: the ultimate answer to the PC-mainframedebate: the Darden Convergence. (the convergence of mainframes,minicomputers and PCs into a single product in 1996) (Final Word)(column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Darden, David A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>By 1996, mainframes, minicomputers and PCs will converge into asingle product, according to the Darden Convergence.andP;  A chart isprovided that maps the performance of the various systems from1960 to the end of the century.andP;  The chart shows that a 1981 PChad the processing power of a 1961 mainframe, and in 1984 that ofa 1968 mainframe, etc.andP;  The chart indicates that PCs pick up sevenyears of mainframe performance every three years: PCs willconverge with minicomputers on Apr 2, 1992, and with mainframes onJan 1, 1996.andP;  Mainframe and minicomputer manufacturers willincorporate PC technology into their products, making theirpost-convergence performance essentially the same as that of PCs.andO;Among the implications of this convergence are that the debateabout the relative merits of PCs and mainframes will be moot, andthat the culture of computing will be turned on its head.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer IndustryIndustry AnalysisOutlookForecastingProcessor SpeedMinicomputersMainframe ComputersMicrocomputersComparison.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   The Darden Convergence. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>